The original film had them found in the wild of the USA, but perhaps they had earlier adventures which led them from Asia to America, making them Siberian chipmunks. In any case, the Siberian chipmunk has a lifespan of 6-10 years while in captivity. If my calculations are correct, with the original film being released in 2007 and their previous undocumented adventures of going from Asia to America taking an estimated 2 years, I can determine that they will probably die in this film.

text: Star Wars Episode 7 Official Trailer views: 76,000,000 (Rising a bit fast) Star Wars Episode 7 Official Trailer likes: 596,000 (Rising Significantly)  Alvin and the Chipmunks Official Trailer views: 1,000,000 (Rising very slowly) Alvin and the Chipmunks Official Trailer likes: 9,100 (Dislikes taking over a significant amount) (Rising very slowly)  Star Wars' fanbase is vastly larger than Alvin and the Chipmunk's Star Wars went on a 25+ year hiatus, with fans anxiously waiting, creating hundreds of video games, including flash games.  Alvin and the Chipmunks went on a 4 year hiatus, it was basically forgotten by everyone in less than 2 years.   More money was spent on Star Wars than Alvin and the Chipmunks.   Star Wars has a massive, extensive universe, with an amazing story, characters, visuals.  Alvin and the Chipmunks has a very small, very limited universe, with the only story being a bunch of chipmunks are on a trip, the characters aren't all that great (Except Simon) and the visuals are pretty good at best.  And yet, there are some people out there asking "Why isn't there anyone watching Alvin and the Chipmunks?" Well, there's your answer, Star Wars is simply better than Alvin and the Chipmunks. Plus, they thought that releasing on the same day as Star Wars was intelligent.

text: I saw this movie on December 20th. My thoughts: It was good. But there were barely any things you thought there would be from the other films, and there were three of them: 1. No David Cross. 2. Jason Lee doesn't have the same house set as he did before. 3. The Chipettes had very little screen time, and all they were doing was sitting in their  chairs, judging the singers, throughout the whole movie. I'm not joking. That's what I saw. Does that mean they were sitting there for a week? Come on.  Going back to what I was saying in number three, I actually thought it was good that they focused more on the Chipmunks, instead of the Chipettes. My overall rating:  2 stars.  The movie isn't bad at all. There were just barely any things that returned from the other films.
